And doctors, lab, x-ray... everybody is working hard, even for those ladies on that TV show who couldn't appreciate how to rock a violin.
And we could not do OUR jobs without CNAs, MAs, unit clerks, PT/OT/ST, Dietitians and Nutritionists, Psych and Social workers, Housekeeping.
So next time you see your nurse, give him or her a pat on the back, a hand shake, or a warm hug. Nurses are among the most dedicated peeps.
And nurses nowadays wear scrubs and a sensible pair of shoes. Some nurses still wear white uniforms, but white is a difficult color to keep.
So the nurse hangs a stethescope around her or his neck for actual medical use... it's not just a pretty accessory. We use it, too!
Oh, and that abdominal aortic aneurysm (Triple A) you're fixin' ta have? We can detect that to by giving a careful listen to the belly area.
We take blood pressure measurements in various places... most commonly the brachial pulse is assessed prior to the BP cuff being inflated.
We listen to bowel sounds, to ensure the pipes are not clogged. Clogged pipes could indicate constipation... or a dreaded ruptured bowel.
We listen to heart sounds in at least five different locations, lung sounds both dorsal and ventral (front sis and backsides and sidsies).
Because we do patient health assessment, both focused on a specific medical issue or head-to-toe on admission.
Now why on earth would a nurse need a stethescope, aside from having one available for the doc to borrow?
I wish I had a dollah bill for every time a doctor asked to borrow my stethoscope. BTW, mine is a master cardiology version, and I am an RN.
